{"title_page": "Skinny Jeanz and a Mic", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Skinny Jeanz and a Mic\n| type       = Studio album\n| artist     = [[New Boyz]]\n| cover      = Skinny Jeans and a Mic.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = September 15, 2009\n| recorded   = 2008&ndash;2009\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Pop-rap]]|[[hyphy]]}}\n| length     = 43:08\n| label      = Shotty, [[Asylum Records|Asylum]], [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n| producer   = Legacy, [[DJ Felli Fel]], Jay-Nari, D&D\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Too Cool to Care]]\n| next_year  = 2011\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Skinny Jeanz and a Mic\n | type        = Studio album\n | single1     = [[You're a Jerk]]\n | single1date = April 2, 2009\n | single2     = [[Tie Me Down]]\n | single2date = August 31, 2009\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Skinny Jeanz and a Mic''''' is the debut [[studio album]] by [[jerkin']] crew and rap duo [[New Boyz]], Legacy and Ben J. It was released on September 15, 2009, via Shotty Music, [[Asylum Records]] and [[Warner Bros. Records]]. The album was heavily influenced by [[jerkin']] music. It received generally positive reviews, being called the sixth best album of 2009 by ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref name=\"NY2\"/> The album was released after the duo brought jerkin' to national attention with their viral hit \"[[You're a Jerk]]\", which later became a commercial success and the first single off their album. The second single \"[[Tie Me Down]]\", featuring [[Ray J]], was released and also was successful. The album debuted at fifty-six on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], and at number twelve on [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] and eight on [[Top Rap Albums]]. The album was produced by [[New Boyz]] member, [[Legacy (rapper)|Legacy]], and also contributions from producers, Jay-Nari, D&D and [[DJ Felli Fel]].\n\n==Background==\nThe album was originally scheduled for release, August 18, 2009, but plans were changed for unknown reasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1615680/20090710/new_boyz.jhtml|title=New Boyz Say They're More Than Just Jerkin' Rappers|publisher=[[MTV News]]|first=Shaheem|last=Reid|date=2009-07-13|accessdate=2010-03-14}}</ref> Legacy received main production credits on the album. In an interview with ''Format Magazine'' he said, \"I started making beats because I didn\u2019t want everybody else\u2019s sound. We wanted our own sound. So, I had no choice but to make my own beats to get that sound.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.formatmag.com/features/boyz/|title=New Boyz|publisher=Format Magazine|first=NeKelia|last=Henderson|date=2009-10-12|accessdate=2010-03-14}}</ref> In an interview with ''Ozone Magazine'', when asked about their music and the revival of the \"newer west\" movement, Ben J stated, \"Everything is becoming positive out here. People are growing out of that old mentality. Rapping about gangs ain\u2019t really what it\u2019s about out here now. Everybody is having fun.\" In the same interview, Legacy said, \"I think music like ours is coming from people being tired of\nthe same ol\u2019 thing. People thought they had to bang to be the cool kid but now the smart kid is the cool kid. People being creative are the people coming up right now.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.ozonemag.com/2009/07/26/ozone-west-jun-2009-patiently-waiting-new-boyz/|title=OZONE West Jun 2009 \u2013 Patiently Waiting: New Boyz|magazine=Ozone Magazine|first=Maurice|last=Garland|date=2009-07-16|accessdate=2010-03-14}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with ''HipHopDX'', Legacy said the album was, \"[It\u2019s] pretty much like the lifestyle and the culture of the typical California teenager put in[to] music. It\u2019s going to surprise a lot of people, because a lot of people think we just make the jerk songs [and] dance music.\"<ref name=\"HipHop\"/> According to Legacy, only two tracks on the album are jerking songs. He also stated that the album is about a lot of different topics, and was quick to point out that most of them were pre-\"Jerk\" stating they were fifteen songs in before 'You're a Jerk'.<ref name=\"HipHop\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.9288/title.the-new-boyz-talk-you-re-a-jerk-dance-craze-album|title=The New Boyz Talk \"You're A Jerk\" Dance Craze, Album|magazine=HipHopDX|first=Sean|last=Lyon|date=2009-06-11|accessdate=2010-04-17}}</ref> Most of the producers on the album were mostly unknown, local producers. Legacy said, \"We have no big producers on our album. All of our producers are like kids\nour age. Everything complements each other, because the style and the music are so new to the game.\"<ref name=\"HipHop\"/>\n\n==Composition==\n{{Listen\n |pos          = left\n |filename     = youreajerk.ogg\n |title        = \"You're a Jerk\"\n |description  = The duo's debut single, a viral dance hit. \n |filename2    = tiemedown.ogg\n |title2       = \"Tie Me Down\"\n |description2 = The album's second single, a collaboration with Ray-J features a [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] tone and [[auto-tune]]d vocals \n}}\n\nMany critics noted<ref name=\"XXL\" /> Several songs are built on the same formula of \"You're a Jerk\", with [[AllMusic]] noting that, \"Dot Com,\" \"Colors,\" \"Turnt,\" and \"So Dope\" (which the chorus is a [[sound bite]] from the 1992 film [[Class Act]]) all have the cheesy drum machines, samples, and off-kilter lyric approach that make \"Jerk\" so good.<ref name=\"ALLMUSICREVIEW\" /> The review also said \"R&B ballad \"Tie Me Down\" featuring smooth Auto-tuned vocals from Ray J, the B.A.S.S.-inspired \"Bunz\", the slow jam \"New Girl,\" and the rollicking \"Cashmere,\" which bumps along like a New Jack rap jam, are nice diversions.\"<ref name=\"ALLMUSICREVIEW\" /> On the album split, ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]'' said, \"The album begins to lose circulation toward its end, when the pair lose their lambent wit in favor of mawkish lover-boy ballads better left to [[Sean Kingston]] albums.\"<ref name=\"LATIMES\" /> Jeff Weiss of the newspaper used \"[[Tie Me Down]]\" as an example, noting that its sounds have \"a saccharine sappiness and contrived tone that feels at odds with the otherwise organic-sounding album.\"<ref name=\"LATIMES\" />\n\nSome points of the work were inspired by [[Pharrell Williams]], [[Kanye West]], and other \"hip-hop style eccentrics\".<ref name=\"NY1\" /> The songs on the album have heavy lyrical underlies, noted by several critics.<ref name=\"XXL\" /><ref name=\"NY1\" /> The comic-esque \"Way 2 Many Chickz\" described as talking about \"a string of almost-conquests better left unvanquished\": \"Chick had a cold sore that looked like [[John McCain]].\" On \"Cashmere\", Ben J and Legacy \"try to outdo each other to win the attention of a young woman, but, predictably, she spurns them both\".<ref name=\"NY1\" /> The lyrics also cover their difference in style, as seen in \"Cricketz\", as Legacy raps, \"Jeans stay skinny like I starve my fabric, Another damn thing/You\u2019ll never see me care about another man\u2019s jeans.\" [[Jon Caramanica]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' responded, \"Baggy has been de rigueur in hip-hop for so long it\u2019s easy to forget that 25 years ago, rappers gladly wore tight denim. Now it\u2019s cause for a fight.\" <ref name=\"NY1\" /> Some of the lyrics use [[double entendre]], with the duo referring to themselves as \"rejects\" and \"jerks\" on \"Dot Com\", which ''The Los Angeles Times'' called \"both a double-entendre for the dance moves spurring the craze, and illustrative of their generation\u2019s reclamation of formerly nerdy archetypes.\"<ref name=\"LATIMES\" />\n\n==Singles==\n\"[[You're a Jerk]]\" was released as the album's first single on April 2, 2009. The song was a viral success, and later succeeded peaked at number twenty-four on the U.S. [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], thirteen on [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] and four on [[Hot Rap Songs]].<ref name=\"Charthistory\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/artist/new-boyz/chart-history/1109704|title=New Boyz Album & Song Chart History|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=2010-04-15}}</ref>\n\n\"[[Tie Me Down]]\" was released as the album's second single on August 31, 2009, it peaked at number twenty-two on the U.S. Billboard Hot 100, and five on Hot Rap Songs. It reached forty two on Hot R&B/Hip Hop Songs, and fared better on [[contemporary hit radio|mainstream]] airplay, the duo's first entry at pop radio,  peaking at twenty-three on the [[Mainstream Top 40 (Pop Songs)]] chart.<ref name=\"Charthistory\"/>\n\nThere are music videos for three of the album's songs, \"Cricketz\" featuring [[Tyga]], \"So Dope\" and \"Dot Com\".<ref>https://itunes.apple.com/us/music-video/cricketz-feat.-tyga/id361150329</ref><ref>https://itunes.apple.com/us/music-video/so-dope/id339586278</ref><ref>https://itunes.apple.com/us/music-video/dot-com/id339574723</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Commercial response===\nThe album debuted at number fifty-six on the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], and spent four weeks on the chart. It debuted and peaked at number eight on the [[Top Rap Albums]] chart and number twelve on the [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] chart.<ref name=\"BILLBOARDINFO\">{{cite magazine|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=new boyz|chart=all}}|title=Skinny Jeanz & A Mic - New Boyz|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=2010-03-14}}</ref> Before falling off the chart in November 2009, the album had sold around 35,000 copies.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.10071/title.hip-hop-album-sales-the-week-ending-11-1-2009|last=Paine|first=Jake|title=Hip Hop Album Sales: The Week Ending 11/1/2009|magazine=HipHopDX|accessdate=2010-04-05}}</ref> The album has sold 133,500 copies til' the beginning of 2011.<ref>http://hiphopencounter.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/rap21.png</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n{{Album ratings\n| title =''Skinny Jeans and a Mic''\n<!-- Reviewers -->\n| rev1 =[[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score ={{rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"ALLMUSICREVIEW\"/>\n| rev2 =[[BBC]]\n| rev2Score =(positive)<ref name=\"BBC\"/>\n| rev3 =''[[The Los Angeles Times]]''\n| rev3Score ={{rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"LATIMES\"/>\n| rev4 =''[[The New York Times]]''\n| rev4Score =(positive)<ref name=\"NY1\"/>\n| rev5 =''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]''\n| rev5Score ={{rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"XXL\"/>\n| rev6 =DJBooth.net\n| rev6Score ={{rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"DJBooth\"/>\n}}\nTim Sendra of [[AllMusic]] gave the album three out of five stars review, and said the album had the  \"cheesy drum machines, samples, and off-kilter lyric approach that make \"[[You're A Jerk|Jerk]]\" so good\", \"the duo stick to the template [of \"Jerk\"], considering the uniqueness of the sound they've created and also the fact that it's a debut record made by teenagers, and an impressive and unfailingly fun debut at that.\" The review goes on to point out that \"the reliance on the \"Jerk\" sound can be a little monotonous, there are enough variations along the way to keep things interesting.\" He also says \"The duo's flow is not incredible but they spit convincingly. If you were looking for undisputedly pop-rap with a fresh sound and a light lyrical touch, the New Boyz debut is a fine destination.\"<ref name=\"ALLMUSICREVIEW\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r1626388|pure_url=yes}}|title=all music (((Skinny Jeanz & A Mic > Overview )))|first=Tim|last=Senda|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=2010-03-11}}</ref> ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]'' said that the album delivered \"unexpected lyrical talent\" but that it lacked \"sonic variety\". The review also goes on to say that the album \"is no hip-hop classic, but rather the breath of fresh air rap needs.\"<ref name=\"XXL\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/online/?p=57195|first=Jonny|last=Alverez|title=New Boyz: Skinny Jeans & a Mic|magazine=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]|date=2009-09-15|accessdate=2010-03-11}}</ref> Jeff Weiss of ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]'' gave the album three stars, commenting that the album \"is a catchy and charismatic debut that should engender pleasant teen nostalgia in anyone old enough to vote and help explain why for the last six months, the kids have been saying out with the old, in with the New Boyz.\".<ref name=\"LATIMES\">{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2009/09/album-review-the-new-boyzskinny-jeans-and-a-mic.html|title=Album Review: New Boyz, 'Skinny Jeanz and a Mic'|first=Jeff|last=Weiss|newspaper=[[LA Times]]|date=2009-09-15|accessdate=2010-03-12}}</ref> The review also said that the album \"successfully strikes a balance between introducing a new sound (the minimalist bass-heavy bounce of jerk music) and style (skinny jeans, Vans and \"colors that ain\u2019t even on the rainbow\"), with traditional teenage themes (girls, the desire for self-expression, adults who don\u2019t understand, girls). The result is a West Coast antidote to the South\u2019s veritable monopoly on homeroom rap\u2014a relentlessly breezy and fun ride through the lives of a pair of class clowns bent on enjoying the face cards that fate dealt.\"<ref name=\"LATIMES\" /> The [[Selby Times]] said that the album \"is about as happening as it gets for teenage music with an attitude, even if it makes adults' eyes roll in disgust.\"<ref name=\"SELBY\">{{cite web|url=http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/music-reviews/New-Boyz-Skinny-Jeans-And.6029976.jp|title=New Boyz: Skinny Jeans And A Mic|publisher=The Selby Times|date=2010-01-31|accessdate=2010-03-12}}</ref> Wendy Roby of [[BBC]] said that, \"But overall their sheer chutzpah wins you over \u2013 and with its day-glo tongue wedged so very firmly in its cheek, Skinny Jeanz and a Mic is hard to resist.\"<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/33nv|title=New Boyz Skinny Jeanz and a Mic Review|date=2010-01-19|accessdate=2010-03-12|first=Wendy|last=Roby|publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref> [[Jon Caramanica]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' called the album \"one of the year\u2019s most charming rap debuts, and certainly the least expected.\"<ref name=\"NY1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/21/arts/music/21boyz.html?_r=1&ref=music|title=Do the Jerk: Skinny Jeans and All That Bouncy, Bawdy Id|first=Jon|last=Caramanica|authorlink=Jon Caramanica|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=2009-09-20|accessdate=2010-03-10}}</ref> In a separate review, he named the album the sixth best album of the year, commenting, \"Emerging from Southern California\u2019s jerk scene, this teenage duo made an album that\u2019s appealingly young, simultaneously wide-eyed and knowingly lewd.\"<ref name=\"NY2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/20/arts/music/20caramanica.html|title=Sumptuous Hip-Hop, Nashville Punk|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|first=Jon|last=Caramanica|date=2009-12-18|accessdate=2010-03-13}}</ref> DJBooth.net's Nathan Slavik was less positive, predicting that the album would be \"the last time we hear from the New Boyz.\"<ref name=\"DJBooth\">{{cite web|url=http://www.djbooth.net/index/albums/review/new-boyz-skinny-jeanz-and-a-mic-09210901/|title=Skinny Jeanz and a Mic Review|publisher=DJBooth.net|first=Nathan|last=Slavik|date=2009-09-21|accessdate=2011-07-25}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Tracklist\n| collapsed       = \n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n|title1           = Cricketz\n|writer1          = Dominic Thomas, Earl Benjamin, [[Tyga|Michael Stevenson]], Keith Brown \n|extra1           = [[Legacy (rapper)|Legacy]]\n|length1          = 3:25\n|note1            = featuring [[Tyga]] \n|title2           = [[You're a Jerk]]\n|writer2          = Thomas, Benjamin\n|extra2           = Legacy\n|length2          = 3:09\n|title3           = Dot Com\n|writer3          = Thomas, Benjamin, Keith Brown\n|extra3           = Legacy\n|length3          = 3:30\n|title4           = Colorz\n|writer4          = Thomas, Benjamin\n|extra4           = Legacy\n|length4          = 3:55\n|title5           = Way 2 Many Chickz\n|writer5          = Thomas, Benjamin\n|extra5           = Legacy\n|length5          = 3:24\n|title6           = Turnt\n|writer6          = Thomas, Benjamin\n|extra6           = Legacy\n|length6          = 3:10\n|title7           = Bunz\n|writer7          = Thomas, Benjamin, David Ellie\n|extra7           = Legacy\n|length7          = 2:49\n|note7            = featuring Kydd-SB\n|title8           = Cashmere\n|writer8          = Thomas, Benjamin\n|extra8           = Legacy\n|length8          = 3:05\n|title9           = So Dope\n|writer9          = Thomas, Benjamin, Ronald Jackson\n|extra9           = Legacy\n|length9          = 3:00\n|title10          = [[Tie Me Down]]\n|writer10         = Thomas, Benjamin, Jason Wilkinson\n|extra10          = Jay-Nari\n|length10         = 2:58\n|note10           = featuring [[Ray J]]\n|title11          = New Girl\n|writer11         = Thomas, Benjamin, Dominique Logan, Darius Logan \n|extra11          = D&D\n|length11         = 3:30\n|note11           = featuring D&D\n|title12          = No More\n|writer12         = Thomas, Benjamin, Eric Bellinger, Keith Brown, Jonathan Castle, Justin Hunt, Guy James, Brandon Lucas\n|extra12          = Legacy\n|length12         = 3:55\n|note12           = featuring O.N.E.\n|title13          = One Night\n|writer13         = Thomas, Benjamin, [[DJ Felli Fel|James Corrine]]\n|extra13          = [[DJ Felli Fel]]\n|length13         = 3:20\n|note13           = \n}}\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = ''[[iTunes]] Bonus Track''\n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n| title14         = Skinny Jeanz \n| extra14         = Legacy\n| writer14        = Thomas, Benjamin\n| length14        = 3:09\n}}\n\n==Charts==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (2009)\n!Peak<br />position\n|-\n|US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]]<ref name=\"BILLBOARDINFO\" />\n|align=\"center\"|56\n|-\n|US [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] (''Billboard'')<ref name=\"BILLBOARDINFO\" />\n|align=\"center\"|12\n|-\n|US [[Top Rap Albums]] (''Billboard'')<ref name=\"BILLBOARDINFO\" />\n|align=\"center\"|8\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Chart (2010)\n!Position\n|-\n|US Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums (''Billboard'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2010/top-r-b-hip-hop-albums|title=2010 Year-End Charts: R&B/Hip-Hop Albums|work=Billboard|access-date=December 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129091347/http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2010/top-r-b-hip-hop-albums|archive-date=January 29, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|68\n|-\n|US Top Rap Albums (''Billboard'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/charts/year-end/2010/top-rap-albums|title=2010 Year-End Charts: Rap Albums|work=Billboard|access-date=December 19, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150101184537/http://www.billboard.com:80/charts/year-end/2010/top-rap-albums|archive-date=January 1, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|33\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|type=album|region=United States|artist=New Boyz|title=Skinny Jeanz and a Mic|award=Gold|relyear=2009}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Good article}}\n\n'''\n\n{{New Boyz}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Skinny Jeanz And A Mic}}\n[[Category:2009 debut albums]]\n[[Category:Asylum Records albums]]\n[[Category:New Boyz albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Skinny Jeanz and a Mic\n| type       = Studio album\n| artist     = [[New Boyz]]\n| cover      = Skinny Jeans and a Mic.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = September 15, 2009\n| recorded   = 2008&ndash;2009\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Pop-rap]]|[[hyphy]]}}\n| length     = 43:08\n| label      = Shotty, [[Asylum Records|Asylum]], [[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]]\n| producer   = Legacy, [[DJ Felli Fel]], Jay-Nari, D&D\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Too Cool to Care]]\n| next_year  = 2011\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Skinny Jeanz and a Mic\n | type        = Studio album\n | single1     = [[You're a Jerk]]\n | single1date = April 2, 2009\n | single2     = [[Tie Me Down]]\n | single2date = August 31, 2009\n}}\n}}\n\n'''''Skinny Jeanz and a Mic''''' is the debut [[studio album]] by [[jerkin']] crew and rap duo [[New Boyz]], Legacy and Ben J. It was released on September 15, 2009, via Shotty Music, [[Asylum Records]] and [[Warner Bros. Records]]. The album was heavily influenced by [[jerkin']] music. It received generally positive reviews, being called the sixth best album of 2009 by ''[[The New York Times]]''.<ref name=\"NY2\"/> The album was released after the duo brought jerkin' to national attention with their viral hit \"[[You're a Jerk]]\", which later became a commercial success and the first single off their album. The second single \"[[Tie Me Down]]\", featuring [[Ray J]], was released and also was successful. The album debuted at fifty-six on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], and at number twelve on [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] and eight on [[Top Rap Albums]]. The album was produced by [[New Boyz]] member, [[Legacy (rapper)|Legacy]], and also contributions from producers, Jay-Nari, D&D and [[DJ Felli Fel]].\n\n==Background==\nThe album was originally scheduled for release, August 18, 2009, but plans were changed for unknown reasons.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1615680/20090710/new_boyz.jhtml|title=New Boyz Say They're More Than Just Jerkin' Rappers|publisher=[[MTV News]]|first=Shaheem|last=Reid|date=2009-07-13|accessdate=2010-03-14}}</ref> Legacy received main production credits on the album. In an interview with ''Format Magazine'' he said, \"I started making beats because I didn\u2019t want everybody else\u2019s sound. We wanted our own sound. So, I had no choice but to make my own beats to get that sound.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.formatmag.com/features/boyz/|title=New Boyz|publisher=Format Magazine|first=NeKelia|last=Henderson|date=2009-10-12|accessdate=2010-03-14}}</ref> In an interview with ''Ozone Magazine'', when asked about their music and the revival of the \"newer west\" movement, Ben J stated, \"Everything is becoming positive out here. People are growing out of that old mentality. Rapping about gangs ain\u2019t really what it\u2019s about out here now. Everybody is having fun.\" In the same interview, Legacy said, \"I think music like ours is coming from people being tired of\nthe same ol\u2019 thing. People thought they had to bang to be the cool kid but now the smart kid is the cool kid. People being creative are the people coming up right now.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.ozonemag.com/2009/07/26/ozone-west-jun-2009-patiently-waiting-new-boyz/|title=OZONE West Jun 2009 \u2013 Patiently Waiting: New Boyz|magazine=Ozone Magazine|first=Maurice|last=Garland|date=2009-07-16|accessdate=2010-03-14}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with ''HipHopDX'', Legacy said the album was, \"[It\u2019s] pretty much like the lifestyle and the culture of the typical California teenager put in[to] music. It\u2019s going to surprise a lot of people, because a lot of people think we just make the jerk songs [and] dance music.\"<ref name=\"HipHop\"/> According to Legacy, only two tracks on the album are jerking songs. He also stated that the album is about a lot of different topics, and was quick to point out that most of them were pre-\"Jerk\" stating they were fifteen songs in before 'You're a Jerk'.<ref name=\"HipHop\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.9288/title.the-new-boyz-talk-you-re-a-jerk-dance-craze-album|title=The New Boyz Talk \"You're A Jerk\" Dance Craze, Album|magazine=HipHopDX|first=Sean|last=Lyon|date=2009-06-11|accessdate=2010-04-17}}</ref> Most of the producers on the album were mostly unknown, local producers. Legacy said, \"We have no big producers on our album. All of our producers are like kids\nour age. Everything complements each other, because the style and the music are so new to the game.\"<ref name=\"HipHop\"/>\n\n==Composition==\n{{Listen\n |pos          = left\n |filename     = youreajerk.ogg\n |title        = \"You're a Jerk\"\n |description  = The duo's debut single, a viral dance hit. \n |filename2    = tiemedown.ogg\n |title2       = \"Tie Me Down\"\n |description2 = The album's second single, a collaboration with Ray-J features a [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] tone and [[auto-tune]]d vocals \n}}\n\nMany critics noted<ref name=\"XXL\" /> Several songs are built on the same formula of \"You're a Jerk\", with [[AllMusic]] noting that, \"Dot Com,\" \"Colors,\" \"Turnt,\" and \"So Dope\" (which the chorus is a [[sound bite]] from the 1992 film [[Class Act]]) all have the cheesy drum machines, samples, and off-kilter lyric approach that make \"Jerk\" so good.<ref name=\"ALLMUSICREVIEW\" /> The review also said \"R&B ballad \"Tie Me Down\" featuring smooth Auto-tuned vocals from Ray J, the B.A.S.S.-inspired \"Bunz\", the slow jam \"New Girl,\" and the rollicking \"Cashmere,\" which bumps along like a New Jack rap jam, are nice diversions.\"<ref name=\"ALLMUSICREVIEW\" /> On the album split, ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]'' said, \"The album begins to lose circulation toward its end, when the pair lose their lambent wit in favor of mawkish lover-boy ballads better left to [[Sean Kingston]] albums.\"<ref name=\"LATIMES\" /> Jeff Weiss of the newspaper used \"[[Tie Me Down]]\" as an example, noting that its sounds have \"a saccharine sappiness and contrived tone that feels at odds with the otherwise organic-sounding album.\"<ref name=\"LATIMES\" />\n\nSome points of the work were inspired by [[Pharrell Williams]], [[Kanye West]], and other \"hip-hop style eccentrics\".<ref name=\"NY1\" /> The songs on the album have heavy lyrical underlies, noted by several critics.<ref name=\"XXL\" /><ref name=\"NY1\" /> The comic-esque \"Way 2 Many Chickz\" described as talking about \"a string of almost-conquests better left unvanquished\": \"Chick had a cold sore that looked like [[John McCain]].\" On \"Cashmere\", Ben J and Legacy \"try to outdo each other to win the attention of a young woman, but, predictably, she spurns them both\".<ref name=\"NY1\" /> The lyrics also cover their difference in style, as seen in \"Cricketz\", as Legacy raps, \"Jeans stay skinny like I starve my fabric, Another damn thing/You\u2019ll never see me care about another man\u2019s jeans.\" [[Jon Caramanica]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' responded, \"Baggy has been de rigueur in hip-hop for so long it\u2019s easy to forget that 25 years ago, rappers gladly wore tight denim. Now it\u2019s cause for a fight.\" <ref name=\"NY1\" /> Some of the lyrics use [[double entendre]], with the duo referring to themselves as \"rejects\" and \"jerks\" on \"Dot Com\", which ''The Los Angeles Times'' called \"both a double-entendre for the dance moves spurring the craze, and illustrative of their generation\u2019s reclamation of formerly nerdy archetypes.\"<ref name=\"LATIMES\" />\n\n==Singles==\n\"[[You're a Jerk]]\" was released as the album's first single on April 2, 2009. The song was a viral success, and later succeeded peaked at number twenty-four on the U.S. [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], thirteen on [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs]] and four on [[Hot Rap Songs]].<ref name=\"Charthistory\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.billboard.com/#/artist/new-boyz/chart-history/1109704|title=New Boyz Album & Song Chart History|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=2010-04-15}}</ref>\n\n\"[[Tie Me Down]]\" was released as the album's second single on August 31, 2009, it peaked at number twenty-two on the U.S. Billboard Hot 100, and five on Hot Rap Songs. It reached forty two on Hot R&B/Hip Hop Songs, and fared better on [[contemporary hit radio|mainstream]] airplay, the duo's first entry at pop radio,  peaking at twenty-three on the [[Mainstream Top 40 (Pop Songs)]] chart.<ref name=\"Charthistory\"/>\n\nThere are music videos for three of the album's songs, \"Cricketz\" featuring [[Tyga]], \"So Dope\" and \"Dot Com\".<ref>https://itunes.apple.com/us/music-video/cricketz-feat.-tyga/id361150329</ref><ref>https://itunes.apple.com/us/music-video/so-dope/id339586278</ref><ref>https://itunes.apple.com/us/music-video/dot-com/id339574723</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n===Commercial response===\nThe album debuted at number fifty-six on the U.S. [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], and spent four weeks on the chart. It debuted and peaked at number eight on the [[Top Rap Albums]] chart and number twelve on the [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums]] chart.<ref name=\"BILLBOARDINFO\">{{cite magazine|url={{BillboardURLbyName|artist=new boyz|chart=all}}|title=Skinny Jeanz & A Mic - New Boyz|magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=2010-03-14}}</ref> Before falling off the chart in November 2009, the album had sold around 35,000 copies.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.hiphopdx.com/index/news/id.10071/title.hip-hop-album-sales-the-week-ending-11-1-2009|last=Paine|first=Jake|title=Hip Hop Album Sales: The Week Ending 11/1/2009|magazine=HipHopDX|accessdate=2010-04-05}}</ref> The album has sold 133,500 copies til' the beginning of 2011.<ref>http://hiphopencounter.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/rap21.png</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\n{{Album ratings\n| title =''Skinny Jeans and a Mic''\n<!-- Reviewers -->\n| rev1 =[[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score ={{rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"ALLMUSICREVIEW\"/>\n| rev2 =[[BBC]]\n| rev2Score =(positive)<ref name=\"BBC\"/>\n| rev3 =''[[The Los Angeles Times]]''\n| rev3Score ={{rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"LATIMES\"/>\n| rev4 =''[[The New York Times]]''\n| rev4Score =(positive)<ref name=\"NY1\"/>\n| rev5 =''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]''\n| rev5Score ={{rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"XXL\"/>\n| rev6 =DJBooth.net\n| rev6Score ={{rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"DJBooth\"/>\n}}\nTim Sendra of [[AllMusic]] gave the album three out of five stars review, and said the album had the  \"cheesy drum machines, samples, and off-kilter lyric approach that make \"[[You're A Jerk|Jerk]]\" so good\", \"the duo stick to the template [of \"Jerk\"], considering the uniqueness of the sound they've created and also the fact that it's a debut record made by teenagers, and an impressive and unfailingly fun debut at that.\" The review goes on to point out that \"the reliance on the \"Jerk\" sound can be a little monotonous, there are enough variations along the way to keep things interesting.\" He also says \"The duo's flow is not incredible but they spit convincingly. If you were looking for undisputedly pop-rap with a fresh sound and a light lyrical touch, the New Boyz debut is a fine destination.\"<ref name=\"ALLMUSICREVIEW\">{{cite web|url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r1626388|pure_url=yes}}|title=all music (((Skinny Jeanz & A Mic > Overview )))|first=Tim|last=Senda|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=2010-03-11}}</ref> ''[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]'' said that the album delivered \"unexpected lyrical talent\" but that it lacked \"sonic variety\". The review also goes on to say that the album \"is no hip-hop classic, but rather the breath of fresh air rap needs.\"<ref name=\"XXL\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.xxlmag.com/online/?p=57195|first=Jonny|last=Alverez|title=New Boyz: Skinny Jeans & a Mic|magazine=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]|date=2009-09-15|accessdate=2010-03-11}}</ref> Jeff Weiss of ''[[The Los Angeles Times]]'' gave the album three stars, commenting that the album \"is a catchy and charismatic debut that should engender pleasant teen nostalgia in anyone old enough to vote and help explain why for the last six months, the kids have been saying out with the old, in with the New Boyz.\".<ref name=\"LATIMES\">{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/music_blog/2009/09/album-review-the-new-boyzskinny-jeans-and-a-mic.html|title=Album Review: New Boyz, 'Skinny Jeanz and a Mic'|first=Jeff|last=Weiss|newspaper=[[LA Times]]|date=2009-09-15|accessdate=2010-03-12}}</ref> The review also said that the album \"successfully strikes a balance between introducing a new sound (the minimalist bass-heavy bounce of jerk music) and style (skinny jeans, Vans and \"colors that ain\u2019t even on the rainbow\"), with traditional teenage themes (girls, the desire for self-expression, adults who don\u2019t understand, girls). The result is a West Coast antidote to the South\u2019s veritable monopoly on homeroom rap\u2014a relentlessly breezy and fun ride through the lives of a pair of class clowns bent on enjoying the face cards that fate dealt.\"<ref name=\"LATIMES\" /> ''The Selby Times'' said that the album \"is about as happening as it gets for teenage music with an attitude, even if it makes adults' eyes roll in disgust.\"<ref name=\"SELBY\">{{cite web|url=http://www.selbytimes.co.uk/music-reviews/New-Boyz-Skinny-Jeans-And.6029976.jp|title=New Boyz: Skinny Jeans And A Mic|publisher=The Selby Times|date=2010-01-31|accessdate=2010-03-12}}</ref> Wendy Roby of [[BBC]] said that, \"But overall their sheer chutzpah wins you over \u2013 and with its day-glo tongue wedged so very firmly in its cheek, Skinny Jeanz and a Mic is hard to resist.\"<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/33nv|title=New Boyz Skinny Jeanz and a Mic Review|date=2010-01-19|accessdate=2010-03-12|first=Wendy|last=Roby|publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref> [[Jon Caramanica]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' called the album \"one of the year\u2019s most charming rap debuts, and certainly the least expected.\"<ref name=\"NY1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/21/arts/music/21boyz.html?_r=1&ref=music|title=Do the Jerk: Skinny Jeans and All That Bouncy, Bawdy Id|first=Jon|last=Caramanica|authorlink=Jon Caramanica|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=2009-09-20|accessdate=2010-03-10}}</ref> In a separate review, he named the album the sixth best album of the year, commenting, \"Emerging from Southern California\u2019s jerk scene, this teenage duo made an album that\u2019s appealingly young, simultaneously wide-eyed and knowingly lewd.\"<ref name=\"NY2\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/12/20/arts/music/20caramanica.html|title=Sumptuous Hip-Hop, Nashville Punk|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|first=Jon|last=Caramanica|date=2009-12-18|accessdate=2010-03-13}}</ref> DJBooth.net's Nathan Slavik was less positive, predicting that the album would be \"the last time we hear from the New Boyz.\"<ref name=\"DJBooth\">{{cite web|url=http://www.djbooth.net/index/albums/review/new-boyz-skinny-jeanz-and-a-mic-09210901/|title=Skinny Jeanz and a Mic Review|publisher=DJBooth.net|first=Nathan|last=Slavik|date=2009-09-21|accessdate=2011-07-25}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Tracklist\n| collapsed       = \n| extra_column    = Producer(s)\n|title1           = Cricketz\n|writer1          = Dominic Thomas, Earl Benjamin, [[Tyga|Michael Stevenson]], Keith Brown \n|extra1           = [[Legacy (rapper)|Legacy]]\n|length1          = 3:25\n|note1            = featuring [[Tyga]] \n|title2           = [[You're a Jerk]]\n|writer2          = Thomas, Benjamin\n|extra2           = Legacy\n|length2          = 3:09\n|title3           = Dot Com\n|writer3          = Thomas, Benjamin, Keith Brown\n|extra3           = Legacy\n|length3          = 3:30\n|title4           = Colorz\n|writer4          = Thomas, Benjamin\n|extra4           = Legacy\n|length4          = 3:55\n|title5           = Way 2 Many Chickz\n|writer5          = Thomas, Benjamin\n|extra5           = Legacy\n|length5          = 3:24\n|title6           = Turnt\n|writer6          = Thomas, Benjamin\n|extra6           = Legacy\n|length6          = 3:10\n|title7           = Bunz\n|writer7          = Thomas, Benjamin, David Ellie\n|extra7           = Legacy\n|length7          = 2:49\n|note7          